<TEXT>
along with the bullets guns and 
food the military needs to wage war theres a precious commodity 
that links the troops in saudi arabia to home the mail 70 tons a 
day of it 
but the systems becoming clogged with boxes of cookies books 
newspapers and letters to any soldier from stateside 
wellwishers courtesy of dear abby campaigns and drives by 
churches and schools 
with christmas around the corner its going to get wrse 
i think were getting so much of it that it bogs down the mail 
from loved ones said sgt jw allen postmaster for the 1st 
tactical fighter wing 
were getting to the point of maximum utilization were 
constantly filling up said air force capt philip jewitt at the 
militarys main sorting center to be honest i dont know 
anybody whod rather get a newspaper in exchange for a loved ones 
letter 
but with christmas in mind reinforcements are on the way 
maj gen william pagonis who heads the army support command 
for operation desert shield said he plans to activate two more 
reserve postal units to help the four units not counting 
volunteers now carrying the mail that will boost the total of 
people working in the mail system to 450 
were handling 70 tons a day thats killing us the united 
states is going superpatriotic said pagonis 
it wouldnt be fair to say the system doesnt have some 
problems were improving conditions every day he said when 
was the us army ever set up across miles of desert 
pagonis is aiming for a delivery time of less than 10 days for 
letters or packages for troops in the desert 
soldiers are sending four tons of mail back home every day 
officers said 
some troops are getting so many old newspapers books and 
cookies from wellmeaning strangers that they send them back from 
the desert to the mail room said staff sgt russ lewis of newark 
calif 
well try to throw them on the trucks but a lot of people 
dont want them he said 
however taxed the system is pagonis says the letterwriting 
campaigns are not interfering with keeping the fighting men 
supplied with essential needs 
i never allow mail to interupt supply im not going to let 
that happen supplies get priority he said 
i know the mails just as important to the troops when i 
see the mail interrupting something i put more guys on supply 
and the generals not about to ask for a slowdown in the dear 
abby and other volunteer operations 
for the one soldier who gets that letter its going to be 
worth it pagonis said 
one marine was tickled to get 300 birthday cards from the 
students at rw kershaw school in mount ephraim nj 
at least we know somebodys thinking about us said cpl 
dominic guinto of the 1st battalion 3rd marine regiment 1st 
marine expeditionary force hell celebrate his 21st birthday on 
nov 1 in the desert 
meanwhile supply lines that stretch 12000 miles back to the 
united states are working at full throttle 
the total tonnage is unavailabe but the system has unloaded 
42000 pieces of equipment ammunition pallets and food crates from 
101 ships and 677 air force transports in 80 days 
thats probably unheard of in history said pagonis who has 
6000 soldiers under his command in vietnam it took five or six 
years to have this many troops on the ground weve done it in 80 
days 
until now cargo has been limited to everything that is combat 
essential now supply ships are bringing in spare parts 
stockpiles of ammunition recreation gear things that make living 
in the desert a little easier that includes winter gear such as 
sweaters and space heaters because the temperatures are beginning 
to cool 
theres been no chokepoint at this time pagonis said we 
have fresh fruit in every foxhole 
but some in the field worry that the desert grit is taking its 
toll on tanks trucks and helicopters as soldiers train for war 
were going through so many parts right now while theyre 
doing their exercises that my biggest concern if the real thing 
happens is rnning out of parts said sgt charles owen 35 of 
mobile ala who works in the marine combat service support 
detachment 
theres usually equipment going down every day it takes a lot 
to get it going again owen said 
whats important is to stockpile critical parts said col alex 
powell commanding officer of the marines direct support group 
instead of just ordering a part that happens to go bad like a 
starter on a tank well assume that weve got 100 tanks look at 
whats happened so far and say that in 90 days were going to need 
150 of these starters he said 
despite gripes about late mail and lack of parts the troops say 
theyre well supplied 
maybe not everything we want but everything we need said 
maj john bates of the 3rd marine regiment asked what he wanted 
that he didnt have bates said beer and ice water 
