<TEXT>
federal regulations that bar the staffs of 
governmentsubsidized family planning clinics from discussing 
abortion with their clients are coming under supreme court 
scrutiny 
although fueled by the continuing struggle over abortion the 
legal dispute being argued before the court today more directly 
involves free speech rights rather than womens right to end their 
pregnancies 
at stake is the information available to the 5 million 
lowincome women who depend on family planning clinics and similar 
health care providers 
several antiabortion organizations are urging the justices to 
use the family clinic case to overturn the 1973 roe vs wade 
decision that legalized abortion 
justice department lawyers defending the regulations at issue 
said the bush administration still favors reversal of the 1973 
decision but they did not say this was the appropriate case for 
such court action 
federal regulations imposed by the reagan administration in 1988 
called for the ban on counseling about abortion but court 
challenges have kept the rules from being enforced virtually 
everywhere 
a federal appeals court upheld the 1988 regulations but other 
federal courts have ruled them an unconstitutional infringement on 
free speech rights 
the justices are expected to resolve the conflicting rulings by 
next july 
last year about 4000 family planning clinics nationwide 
received about 140 million in federal assistance 
the family planning clinic program enacted by congress as title 
x of the public health service act pays for creating and operating 
the clinics for most clinics federal money accounts for only a 
portion perhaps 10 percent of their budgets 
challengers of the regulations say they represent a kind of 
viewpoint discrimination 
women who have come to rely on title x for medically sound 
advice will be misled they told the court in written briefs 
the silence of a trusted doctor on the subject of abortion will 
lead many women to believe that abortion is not an appropriate or 
medically indicated option for them 
but bush administration lawyers argue that the government may 
choose to favor childbirth over abortion when deciding how to spend 
taxpayer money 
the clinics always have been banned from using federal money to 
perform abortions but regulations originally let the clinic staffs 
doctors and counselors tell women about the abortion option and 
make referrals 
after those regulations drew criticism from antiabortion 
groups the reagan administration said the clinics may not 
encourage promote or advocate abortion as a method of family 
planning or distribute written materials about abortion 
under the 1988 regulations a woman who visited a federally 
funded family planning clinic and asked about abortion would have 
to be told that the clinic staff does not consider abortion an 
appropriate method of family planning 
staff members then could offer help in obtaining prenatal care 
the high court has not been the sole battlefield legislation to 
sweep away the counseling ban was introduced in congress last week 
and is expected to be reintroduced when the new congres convenes 
in january 
i dont think this is so much a prochoice or prolife 
question said rep john porter rill a sponsor of the house 
bill to lift the ban its a question of counseling of providing 
full information 
</TEXT>
