<TEXT>
international air traffic is expected to increase 
by about 8 percent this year and more than 6 percent in each of the 
next four years with the far east experiencing the most growth 
the leading industry group says 
guenter eser the german director general of the international 
air transport association iata said sunday that the forecasts 
were set before the effects of the persian gulf crisis on passenger 
traffic became clear 
regardless he said the industrys major problem continues to 
be the lack of airport and airspace capacity and this is likely to 
be the case for a number of years to come 
the problem remains most severe in europe but is rapidly 
increasing in the far east eser said in his report to 
associations annual assembly 
the gulf crisis which has raised fuel and insurance costs 
tightened a profit squeeze on the industry he said 
overall profits by member airlines on international scheduled 
flights dropped sharply last year to 04 percent on revenues of 
1445 billion the lowest margin since 1986 
it is impossible to forecast the outcome for the full year 
1990 but the industry aggregate result is probably not going to 
be very good said eser 
iata member airlines carried nearly 212 million international 
passengers last year a 7 percent rise 
traffic is expected to grow 8 percent this year 69 percent in 
1991 and remain at about 65 percent annually through 1994 latest 
iata figures showed 
the far east is the fastest expanding area with nearly 10 
percent average annual growth forecast for northeastern asia and 
88 percent for the southeastern region 
iata which groups 200 airlines worldwide helps coordinate fare 
levels ticketing and other areas of airline operations 
</TEXT>
