<TEXT>
the temperature in the coal mine 3900 
feet down had hit 100 degrees when volodya kyechins vision started 
to blur then the rock floor became rubbery and the dimly lit 
shaft went black 
kyechi awoke hours later on the surface with a case of heat 
stroke over the next nine years the stout ukrainian developed 
high blood pressure lost half his pay and began dreaming of 
leaving the mines for good 
the average life expectancy of a soviet coal miner is 48 years 
they can retire at 55 but only 5 percent reach that age 
the work conditions are hard and ive come to the conclusion 
that i should leave the mine said the 40yearold kyechin 
sitting with his wife tanya at a table in his apartment on the 
outskirts of this industrial city 
soviet miners are relatively well paid earning an average of 
375 rubles a month 50 percent more than the national average but 
no matter what the pay kyechin said whats the point to go 
underground where each time nobody knows what will happen 
miners from across the soviet union echoed that sentiment at a 
fiveday congress in donetsk last week accusing the staterun 
union of failing to represent their interests they voted to form 
the countrys first independent nationwide labor union 
among their principal demands are safety improvements and a say 
in the operation of their mines 
kyechin a miner for nearly 20 years said he would wait to see 
what the new union promises before joining i need to know what 
they would do for me he said 
a television flickered in the comfortable twobedroom apartment 
as the couple poured out their lives over a feast that included 
caviar and vodka both difficult to find in stores 
as a department store manager tanya is plugged into a network 
of contacts who help each other obtain the latest goods whenever 
and wherever they show up 
if we come across a can of fish we buy not one but 10 and 
distribute them among friends she said 
the walls and floors of most rooms were covered with valuable 
bukharan rugs its better to put your money into such things 
kyechin said and a china cabinet stretched across the living room 
wall jammed with a halfdozen sets of fine hardtofind dishes 
the kyechins and their two daughters ages 14 and 6 live in a 
block of prefabricated apartment buildings on the outskirts of 
donetsk a sprawling city of 12 million there are some 40 mines 
within the city limits and about 80 others scattered across the 
hilly coal basin 
with lax enforcement of safety rules and unreliable medical 
care mining is one of the countrys most hazardous jobs an 
average of 800 soviet miners die on the job every year 55 died in 
the united states in 1988 
among other problems the extreme depth of many soviet mines 
makes it difficult to ventilate them and lower the heat generated 
by churning machinery and the earth itself 
most countries prohibit mining when the heat reaches a certain 
level soviet miners say their bosses ignore such rules in a 
heedless drive to win bonuses for fulfilling plans or avoid 
punishment for failing 
the deputy director of the mine told the doctor not to write 
down heat stroke kyechin said bitterly recounting his collapse 
in 1981 he said let it be an ordinary case of accidental 
trauma 
if heat stroke had been reported kyechin explained a committee 
would have questioned the mines supervisers about it and of 
course they would catch hell from their superiors and would make 
less money 
kyechin said he protested at first then capitulated deciding 
his relations with the mine director were too important to be 
risked 
if you are against them you are nothing he said 
after the heat stroke episode kyechin began to suffer high 
blood pressure over the next nine years he was transferred from 
mine to mine around the donetsk basin 
on aug 6 while working in a ventilation shaft he suffered 
heat stroke again kyechin said he was hospitalized for nearly a 
month with high blood pressure then released with an 
occupational disease and given a job as a tunneler which pays 
260 rubles a month about 480 
even with additional compensation for his illness kyechins 
salary is now little more than half the 700 rubles that he once 
earned as a chief engineer and that allowed him to fill his 
apartment with valuables 
because of his long absence from work he also lost a chance to 
buy a car through the official union 
fed up with his treatment by superiors all members of the 
communist party kyechin ended his 20year party membership 
the party does nothing theres nothing in it for our 
future he said 
now kyechin has his eye on a new career an engineer by 
training he has a dream of forming a cooperative to repair and 
remodel apartments i was even thinking of buying a shop he 
said 
