wouldnt know a birdie from a bogey are getting in on the action 
acquiring golf club memberships for speculation as if they were 
commodities futures has become a lucrative business 
mana of the golf association said a membership at green valley 
golf course had gone up nearly 700 percent in three years to 
800000 baht or 32000 
even so club memberships remain cheaper than in japan taiwan 
singapore and hong kong golfers and investors from those 
countries are lining up for the leading thai clubs some of which 
have had to place quotas on foreigners 
golf was introduced by thai royalty in the 1920s it has 
attracted the elite ever since and spread to other classes because 
of economic prosperity tourism and the sports growing worldwide 
popularity 
the japanese including members of the large expatriate 
community frequently describe playing here as being in golfers 
heaven greens fees at luxurious uncrowded clubs are about 40 
and low labor costs permit levels of course maintenance and service 
that are rare in other countries 
many golfing parties have a trail of caddies often young women 
who carry portable stools umbrellas cold drinks and towels as 
well as clubs 
at home japanese golfers must reserve playing time far in 
advance then battle weekend traffic to reach congested courses at 
clubs in the tokyo area nonmembers pay at least 240 for 18 
holes meals and transportation 
south korea and taiwan closer than thailand still are favored 
foreign destinations for japans 15 million golfers but the thais 
expect their traffic to grow travel agencies in japan offer 
fiveday allinclusive golf tours for about 1600 the cost of 
half a dozen rounds at home 
critics of the golf explosion say valuable farm land is being 
lost and the environment harmed in some areas officials have 
questioned whether investing millions in a sport for the wealthy is 
appropriate for a developing nation 
promoters argue that golf courses provide more higherpayed 
jobs than the same land devoted to agriculture they say courses 
are environmental assets in urban areas serving as the green belts 
that government planning has not provided 
