<TEXT>
a rekindled dispute over specks of inhospitable 
rock in the east china sea is feeding antijapanese sentiment in 
quarters already fearful that tokyo is drifting away from pacifism 
the five tiny islands the largest only 25 miles in diameter 
and three rocks are claimed by japan china and taiwan the area is 
considered a rich fishing ground and is believed to contain oil 
japan calls the archipelago the senkakus but china and taiwan 
know the islands as the diaoyutai after a decade in abeyance the 
argument over them was revived by reports in taiwan that a 
rightwing japanese group planned to renovate a lighthouse on the 
main island 
two fishing vessels carried taiwanese politicians and athletes 
to the islands on oct 21 in an attempt to reinforce taiwans 
claim but were turned back by patrol boats of the japanese coast 
guard 
in hong kong about 10000 people turned out for a rally and 
march to demand that japan give up its claim to the islands 
the confrontation comes at a sensitive time for tokyo 
many asian nations that were brutally occupied by japan during 
world war ii already have expressed concern about a government 
proposal now before japans parliament to send noncombat troops to 
the persian gulf 
that bill would allow the first overseas deployment of japanese 
soldiers since the war many believe sending the troops would 
violate japans postwar constitution which forbids it to use force 
in international disputes 
taiwan and china usually at loggerheads because of their rival 
claims to be the legitimate government of all china have objected 
strongly to japans sending coast guard vessels to the disputed 
islands which are 120 miles northeast of taiwan and 95 miles 
northwest of nishiomotejima a japanese island 
protesters in taiwan which was a japanese colony for 50 years 
until world war ii ended have burned the japanese flag thrown 
eggs outside japans representative office in taipei and vow to 
launch another voyage to the islands 
japan has to recognize the diaoyutai islands are our 
territory protest leader lee chinghwa said last week they 
should stop expanding militarism 
probeijing newspapers in hong kong which reverts from british 
to chinese sovereignty in 1997 have printed emotional editorials 
on the islands that recall japans expansionist past 
china has been a victim of japanese militarism the ta kung 
pao said there still exists a widespread sentiment among the 
chinese people opposing militarism 
a fullpage newspaper advertisement by the hong kong 
professional teachers union made a clear connection between the 
island dispute and fears of renewed japanese militarism 
protect diaoyutai teach the next generation it said the 
ad included photographs of chinese slaughtered by japanese soldiers 
in world war ii 
japan has repeatedly denied any intention of reviving 
militarism 
it incorporated the islands in 1895 the united states 
administered them from the end of world war ii until 1972 when 
they were returned to japan 
china has claimed the chain since ancient times the chinese 
nationalist government now on taiwan contends the islets came 
under its sovereignty in 1945 when japan was defeated 
a 1968 united nations report said large oil deposits may lie in 
nearby seabeds japan shelved a joint exploration plan with china 
in 1979 because they were too far apart on the sovereignty issue 
the foreign ministry says fishermen recently refurbished the 
12yearold light and want it to be designated an official 
navigation beacon but that the maritime safety agency has made no 
decision on the application the ministry said it knew of no plans 
by any rightwing group to make further changes 
prime minister toshiki kaifu has been quoted as saying japan 
would act prudently on the lighthouse matter foreign ministry 
spokesman taizo watanabe has said there are no plans to have the 
navy patrol the islands 
in taiwan chang lungyi of the institute of international 
relations said he did not see the island incident as a sign of 
japan becoming a military power but added 
japan could easily transform its welldeveloped industries to 
making weapons and people are concerned that it would quickly build 
up its military power 
some commentators in tokyo question whether fear of japanese 
militarism is the main factor 
yozo yokota professor of international law at international 
christian university believes china may see a chance to reinforce 
its claim to the islands while japan is trying to project a world 
image of peacemaker 
taiwan which has been isolated diplomatically because of its 
claim to china may want to demonstrate that it is a regional 
