<TEXT>
for 120 years the machinery at 
cheshire mills turned out textiles and helped weave the fabric of a 
community 
on sunday about 50 former employees gathered to remember that 
community spirit and how that fabric was torn when the decline of 
the textile industry in new england forced cheshire mills to close 
20 years ago 
it cast a tremendous pall over the town when it happened 
said warren thayer who was office manager when the mill closed 
it was like your security blanket was gone 
wellpreserved and still housing a descendant business of the 
cheshire mills the mill buildings and much of the center of the 
small town population of fewer than 1000 were designated a 
national historic landmark in 1977 
thayer who took part in the reunion organized by a historic 
preservation group said he joined the company full time in 1956 
50 years after his father went to work at cheshire mills for a 
time his family lived in mill housing 
you lived with this for many years it was a very 
paternalistic organization he said we always felt that 
thered always be cheshire mills 
the thayers were one of many families who sent multiple 
generations to work at the mill or at harris mill next door 
even cheshire mills president at its closing john colony jr 
was a descendant of josiah colony who founded the mill about 1850 
colony said it was hard to shut the mill that was practically the 
sole source of employment in harrisville 
it was a working plant and it was the spine of the town 
colony said a lot of people around here working in the mill were 
fifth sixth generation we felt we had a unique responsibility to 
them 
but the us textile industry suffered in the face of cheap 
foreign labor after world war ii much as the british textile 
industry suffered from american competition that peaked during the 
civil war said colonys son john chick colony iii 
we did it to the british and the japanese did it to us he 
said 
the closing came as a shock to the 30 to 50 employees still 
working at the mill that once had employed about 300 
colony said he called shop overseers into his office one by one 
in early october 1970 and sent them out to tell the workers the 
company would shut down in two weeks 
the employees retired moved away or went to work elsewhere in 
the area a few found work at harrisville designs founded by the 
colonys the year after cheshire mills closed it continues to carry 
on mill work in a small way 
harrisville designs which employs about 25 and is housed in 
some of the old cheshire mills and harris mill buildings makes 
looms and yarn for home weavers 
the yarn is made on some of the same machines that spun thread 
for cheshire mills fabrics 
every year for nearly 150 years woolen yarn has been spun 
in this town chick colony said its a tradition 
