<TEXT>
private banks have begun asking the 
agriculture department to make good on 2 billion worth of credit 
guarantees for the sale of wheat rice and other commodities to 
iraq 
not all of the 2 billion is coming due at once however the 
loans are spread out some of them running through 1995 or later 
the guarantees mostly involve two export credit programs 
called gsm102 and gsm103 that are operated by usda to boost sales 
of farm products to selected overseas buyers 
unlike concessional or longterm programs such as food for 
peace these are for shorter periods involving commercial loans 
underwritten by private banks 
the gsm102 program provides credit and repayment over six 
months to three years a wide variety of us farm products are 
exported to dozens of foreign countries with these arrangements 
under gsm103 an intermediate program loans can run from three 
to 10 years and focus on products with longer economic lifetimes 
such as breeding livestock 
the programs are backed up by the departments commodity credit 
corp and are administered by the foreign agricultural service the 
ccc also is the financing agency for all federal commodity support 
programs 
no money is lent directly by the department once a country is 
approved for the guarantee private lenders and exporters work out 
a plan with the foreign buyer subject to usda approval 
larry mcelvain director of ccc operations for the foreign 
agricultural service said claims are coming in now every day 
from lenders who want their payments for grain sold to iraq 
no estimate of the number of credit guarantee claims or amounts 
was readily available 
what you want to understand about the claims is that we dont 
just pay out the 2 billion all at once he said that is 
because lenders cant file a claim until it comes due 
iraq had been buying us farm commodities with credit 
guarantees since 1983 and had an excellent record of repayment 
mcelvain said 
there has never been a claim filed or paid on iraq until this 
situation here he said 
this situation began aug 2 when iraq invaded kuwait as a 
result president bush severed all trade with baghdad including 
further credit sales of farm commodities 
the annual credit line under the guarantee program was at a peak 
of slightly more than 1 billion in fiscal 1989 for 1990 the year 
that ended sept 30 iraq had been cleared for 500 million with 
another 500 million available subject to further review 
 
washington ap moderately strong demand for highprotein meal 
and vegetable oil is helping bolster soybean prices this season 
according to agriculture department analysts 
a major factor however is the size of the 1990 soybean 
harvest currently estimated at 182 billion bushels a slight 
decline from 1989 output 
overall yields bushels per acre are expected to be near 
average and about the same as last years the departments 
economic research service said in a recent outlook report 
accounting for the drop in production is a reduction in acreage 
planted in 1990 more than three million under the 1989 level 
soybean use in the 199091 marketing year that began sept 1 is 
expected to be up slightly from last season the total crush by 
processors to make meal and oil is estimated at 118 billion 
bushels up 3 percent the report said exports of beans are 
expected to drop slightly this season to 615 million bushels 
the domestic use of soybean meal in 199091 is expected to rise 
further from last seasons record level 
a profitable livestock production outlook aided by moderate 
grain prices should boost meal use the report said in the 
export market expected soybean meal sales to the soviet union and 
latin america account for a nearly 10 percent surge in exports over 
last year to 55 million tons 
the domestic use of soybean oil is forecast to match last years 
record although oil exports are expected to trail 198990 the 
report said 
economists projected the farm price of soybeans in 199091 at an 
average of 570 to 7 per bushel up 570 last marketing year 
 
