<TEXT>
president bush is expected to sign an overhaul 
of the nations immigration laws that will substantially boost the 
number of immigrants allowed into the united states each year 
especially those with special job skills 
the first major rewrite of immigration law in a quartercentury 
was approved by congress late saturday as it rushed to adjournment 
white house spokeswoman alixe glen said the legislation had the 
presidents support 
the bill would boost the current limit of 490000 a year on 
legal immigrants to 645000 in each fiscal year through 1994 and 
675000 thereafter the measure keeps reuniting families as its 
primary test but also would open the door to foreigners with 
special skills those who are wealthy and even some shunned for 
years for political or medical reasons such as aids 
the measure assigns the first 465000 visas each year to the 
family preference category with an estimated 220000 of those 
going to immediate relatives of us citizens at the same time it 
earmarks 40000 visas for individuals from italy poland ireland 
and other traditional immigrant sources who have been virtually 
shut out for the past 20 years 
it also would remove bans on immigration for persons because of 
homosexuality 
in that period us immigration priority has been extended to 
those from asia and latin america with few coming from europe 
africa or other regions 
the bill also would relax political restrictions dating to the 
1950s when sen joe mccarthy rwis fought to ban many 
categories of immigrants as part of his crusade against communism 
the secretary of state still will be able to bar individuals for 
political reasons however 
the government also would be allowed to remove aids and other 
diseases from the medical list for which a person may be denied 
entry any decision on whether to do so is up to the bush 
administration 
