<TEXT>
the supreme court today agreed to resolve a 
dispute over black lung benefits that may affect 650 million in 
claims by coal miners and their families 
the court said it will decide how difficult it should be for 
mining companies to challenge claims by as many as 3500 miners 
the court was asked to settle conflicting rulings from federal 
appeals courts that have studied the issue in cases from 
pennsylvania and west virginia 
the bush administration sided with the coal companies in seeking 
to limit the ability of some workers and their families to receive 
benefits 
justice department lawyers said coal mine operators should be 
allowed to show that disabled or deceased miners did not suffer 
from black lung disease or that work in the mines did not cause 
their disability 
the government also noted that black lung benefits may exceed 
185000 per miner or family 
the disease also called pneumoconiosis is a lung disorder 
caused by breathing coal dust over a long period of time 
the supreme court in a related 1988 ruling spared the coal 
mining industry from paying potentially billions of dollars in 
benefits to as many as 155000 miners the justices barred 
reopening claims that were denied in the late 1970s and early 
1980s 
but that ruling left open the issue raised in the dispute acted 
on today the validity of labor department regulations making it 
easier for mine operators to deny benefit claims 
the regulations give the companies the opportunity to dispute 
evidence that miners are suffering from black lung or that they 
were incapacitated by their work in the mines 
earlier regulations adopted by the department of health 
education and welfare said the only way the benefits could be 
denied is with proof a miner is still working is capable of 
working in the mines or is doing comparable work 
some federal appeals courts have upheld the labor department 
rules others have said they conflict with a 1977 federal law aimed 
at helping disabled miners 
congress created a special fund to pay off claims by miners with 
the disease and required mine operators to contribute to the fund 
the cases are pauley vs bethenergy mines 891714 clinchfield 
coal co vs office of workers compensation 90113 consolidation 
coal co vs workers compensation program 90114 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

