the supreme court today let stand a ruling 
that boosted a federal judges power to order predominantly white 
suburban schools to accept innercity black students 
the justices without comment rejected an appeal by three 
kansas city mo suburban school districts facing such a 
desegregation order 
the case is an outgrowth of a longstanding court battle over 
desegregation of kansas citys public schools 
the fight led last april to an important supreme court ruling 
that federal judges may order local officials to raise property 
taxes to help desegregate public schools 
that 54 ruling upheld key features of a 1985 decision by us 
district judge russell clark in a 1977 lawsuit by black parents 
seeking to reverse the decline of the citys predominantly black 
schools 
the case acted on today grew out of clarks 1985 order that 
missouri officials pay for transportation and tuition of black 
students in kansas city who choose to transfer to predominantly 
white suburban schools 
clark described the plan as voluntary on the part of the 
suburban schools and the black students 
but school officials in the suburban districts of north kansas 
city lees summit and independence said they are being coerced 
into accepting the black transfers 
they asked the high court to overturn a may ruling by the 8th 
us circuit court of appeals that said clarks 1985 order is being 
ignored unlawfully 
since 1985 the appeals court said not a single suburban 
school district has admitted a single black student from kansas 
city pursuant to a plan negotiated by the state and the suburban 
school districts further delay cannot be countenanced 
the appeals court noted that 134 black students from kansas city 
applied for admission into the three suburban school districts in 
1988 the appeals court said the suburban districts did not admit 
the students apparently due to worries the state would not 
reimburse the costs 
after the black students were denied admission they filed a new 
lawsuit that was assigned to us district judge joseph e stevens 
jr 
stevens threw out the suit last year but the 8th circuit court 
in its may ruling reversed stevens and reassigned the case to 
clark with instructions to come up with a plan for transferring 
black students to the suburban schools 
the appeals court said the previous refusal of the suburban 
schools to admit the blacks raised questions about whether they 
were practicing unlawful racial bias 
in the appeal acted on today the suburban school officials said 
their districts have no history of racial bias and said it is 
unfair to use their refusal to admit students from another city as 
evidence of discrimination 
the appeals court is using sheer force to impose its values 
on public schools that have no record of racial bias the officials 
said 
the supreme court in 1974 struck down a detroitarea school 
desegregation plan that required students to be bused across ity 
boundaries the justices said such remedies are inappropriate 
unless all districts involved contributed to the segregation 
the case acted on today is lees summit vs naylor 90391 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

