<TEXT>
the supreme court today refused to let any new 
york utility force customers through the rates they pay to 
subsidize its charitable contributions 
the justices without comment let stand a ruling by new yorks 
highest court that said allowing publicly regulated utilities to 
include such charitable giving in their rates violates customers 
rights 
lawyers for the new york telephone co and rochester gas and 
electric corp told the justices the state court ruling creates a 
revolutionary new federal right with alarming national 
implications 
about half the states and even some federal regulatory agencies 
deem reasonable levels of charitable contributions ordinary 
business expenses that may be built into a utility companys 
customer rates 
the new york public service commission which regulates utility 
rates in that state first allowed charitable giving to be included 
in the ratebase in 1970 
joseph cahill a resident of fishkill ny and a new york 
telephone customer challenged the commissions policy so did 
state attorney general robert abrams in a separate lawsuit against 
rochester gas and electric 
the suits were combined and a state trial judge ruled that 
policy allowing charitable contributions to be included in the 
ratebase violates cusomers freespeech rights 
the new york court of appeals upheld that ruling last may 
ratepayers are entitled to protection against forced financial 
support for causes and messages personally distasteful to them 
the state court said the utilities have not fulfilled their 
burden of justification for imposing on their ratepayers rather 
than on their shareholders the bill for their selected 
philanthropy 
the state court relied heavily on a 1977 supreme court ruling in 
which the justices barred unions from using mandatory fees 
collected from nonmembers they represent for anything unrelated to 
collective bargaining 
the 1977 ruling was one in a series of decisions in which the 
high court said the constitutions first amendment not only 
protects the right to speak and associate freely but also the right 
not to speak or associate 
documents submitted in the new york case appeared to disagree 
over just what charitable contributions were at issue 
lawyers for new york telephone said the company does not 
engage in political religious or ideological giving 
but the state courts ruling last may said new york telephone 
and rochester gas and electric had contributed to numerous 
charities including politically and religiously active 
organizations 
cahills lawyers said he is a lifelong roman catholic who 
objected among other things to charitable contributions made to 
organizations that advocate abortion rights 
in a friendofthecourt brief united ways of america urged 
the justices to reverse the state court ruling united ways said 
that 558 million of the 682 million in corporate contributions 
it received last year came from utility companies 
the case is new york telephone co vs cahill 90255 
</TEXT>
