<TEXT>
the supreme court today refused to let new 
york prison authorities give short haircuts to newly arrived 
inmates belonging to a jamaicabased religion called rastafarians 
the court without comment left intact a ruling that the 
haircut policy violates the inmates religious freedom 
rastafarians adherents of a jamaicabased religion founded on a 
belief that the late ethiopia emperor haile selassie is god have 
religious scruples against men cutting or combing their hair 
they wear their hair in ropelike strands known as dreadlocks 
at new york prisons all incoming inmates are required to get a 
short haircut and have an identification photograph made the 
photograph is to be used in the event of an escape 
after the photo is taken however inmates are free to grow 
their hair to whatever length they please 
rastafarian inmates challenged the haircut policy in 1979 and 
for nearly six years negotiated with prison officials in search of 
a settlement 
a federal judge in 1986 and in subsequent rulings barred 
prison authorities from enforcing the initial haircut policy the 
2nd us circuit court of appeals upheld the haircut policy ban 
last may 
accepting the existence of reasonable security concerns we 
find there is an alternative that can accommodate both parties 
the appeals court said 
it noted that us district judge louis l stanton had found 
that pulling an inmates hair back in a ponytail while taking the 
identification photo would meet a prisons security needs 
prison officials had argued that stanton was wrong about that 
but the appeals court said the officials failed to establish that 
the accommodation here has more than a minimal effect on valid 
penological interests 
in the appeal acted on today new york prison authorities said 
the appeals court ruling conflicts with a pair of 1987 supreme 
court decisions on inmate rights 
in one the court gave states sweeping power to prevent inmates 
from corresponding with inmates in other prisons in the other the 
justices ruled that prison officials acted properly when forbidding 
some muslims from attending weekly prison worship services 
the case is coughlin vs benjamin 90307 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

