<TEXT>
an 11yearold boy who won and then lost a 
95 million award against the maker of an antinausea drug his 
mother took during pregnancy lost a supreme court appeal today 
the justices over one dissenting vote let stand a ruling that 
threw out sekou ealys legal victory over marion merrell dow inc 
justice byron r white voted to hear arguments in the case but 
four votes are needed to grant such review 
sekous mother sandra took the drug bendectin while pregnant 
and he was born with defects in his hands and arms 
sekou has three fingers on one hand and four on the other and 
no thumbs his arms are underdeveloped and locked at the elbows 
according to court papers sekou has undergone weekly 
psychiatric therapy to address his mental fixation that his parents 
cut off his fingers to punish him for being naughty 
bendectin was marketed between 1957 and 1983 by 
richardsonmerrell inc now marion merrell dow based in kansas 
city mo more than 30 million women used the drug 
the company stopped selling bendectin in 1983 although the 
federal drug administration never has rescinded approval of the 
drug 
after a federal court trial in the district of columbia where 
the ealys lived a jury awarded sekou 20 million in compensatory 
damages and 75 million in punitive damages 
us district judge june l green set aside the punitivedamages 
award but let stand the 20 million compensatorydamages award 
the us circuit court of appeals here overturned that award 
last march 
the appeals court ruled that the expert testimony used in an 
attempt to link bendectin to the birth defects was without 
scientific foundation 
it may well be that future scientific research will generate 
an adequate basis for an experts opinion that bendectin 
caused a plaintiffs birth defects the appeals court said 
until that day the existing body of published epidemiological 
studies all finding no significant statistical association between 
ingestion of bendectin and birth defects must be recognized as the 
measuring stick for the admissibility of expert testimony on this 
issue the appeals court said 
in the appeal acted on today lawyers for sekou said the appeals 
courts treatment of testimony by expert witnesses conflicts with 
how nine other federal appeals courts have dealt with expert 
testimony 
the appeal argued that the appeals court at least should order a 
new trial rather than throw out the suit against the drug 
manufacturer 
the case is ealy vs richardsonmerrell 90225 
</TEXT>
