<TEXT>
a united nations conference on global warming 
opened today and a top un official warned that only radical 
changes can save the world from a climate disaster 
mostafa k tolba the head of the un environment program said 
the threat of global warming is potentially more catastrophic 
than any other threat in human history 
such warming could trigger famine by disrupting agriculture and 
coastal areas could be flooded if sea levels are raised by melting 
of glaciers and the greenland ice sheet 
scientists believe about half of global warming is caused by 
carbon dioxide gas from fossil fuel burning other greenhouse 
gases are methane nitrous oxide and chemicals called 
chlorofluorocarbons or cfcs 
the gases increase the atmospheres tendency to trap heat like 
a greenhouse 
nothing short of action which affects every individual can 
forestall global catastrophe tolba said nothing less than a 
complete change in attitudes and lifestyles will succeed 
the gathering brought together about 500 scientists from around 
the world who are to chart a comprehensive new program with 
proposals on how to counter global warming or the greenhouse 
effect 
the conference will wind up with a twoday meeting of about 80 
government ministers several heads of government including 
britains prime minister margaret thatcher and french prime 
minister michel rocard are to attend 
the united states still opposed to mandatory restrictions on 
emissions of the chemicals involved is represented by a 
lowerranking official john knauss head of the national oceanic 
and atmospheric administration 
the opening of the geneva conference coincided with a meeting of 
environment ministers of the 12nation european community to 
address carbon dioxide emission controls 
at the geneva session a final declaration on nov 7 will 
provide the basis for the first formal negotiations on an accord on 
fighting global warming the pact is to be ready for signing in 
mid1992 
tolba said the convention must spell out specific commitments to 
cut emissions but he said the industrialized nations which emit 
threefourths of all manmade greenhouse gases must act now and 
not wait for the agreement 
the longer we delay the worse the disaster will be for our 
children and for our childrens children he said 
curbing emissions will cost vast sums and will demand great 
changes in economic legal and institutional systems tolba said 
but he said the cost of inaction would be far greater 
developing nations he said would need more time funds and 
access to western technology to reduce emissions 
during the past two years more than 1000 scientists from 70 
countries have compiled a bulky report for the conference which 
list grim scenarios of what might happen unless action is taken to 
reduce global warming 
they predict that continuing on the current course would send 
global temperatures up 54 degrees fahrenheit by the end of the 
next century the fastest rise in 10000 years 
barring countermeasures global sea levels would rise by about 
two feet the report said in the next century rising sea levels 
could flood tens of thousands of miles of densely populated 
shorelines 
the warming trend would also disrupt agricultural production 
worldwide 
but the un food and agriculture administration in a position 
paper prepared for the geneva conference said the overall effect 
on global farming could actually be positive because of the opening 
up of arable lands toward the poles but in some vulnerable 
regions the effect may be very serious it added 
experts generally agree that the trend toward a warmer earth 
cannot be stopped but could be mitigated by a shifting to other 
forms of energy and stopping the destruction of forests around the 
world they agree much more research on the problem is needed 
</TEXT>
