offered to call a friend or relative who could give her a ride 
home but that she declined his offer 
bells car had been stopped in the parkland area of pierce 
county south of tacoma and about five miles from the womans home 
court records indicate the area has the highest violentcrime rate 
in the county outside of tacoma 
the temperature was 50 degrees and the woman as wearing only a 
blouse and jeans she says that after walking a halfblock toward 
her home and having turned down several ride offers from strangers 
she accepted one from an unknown man 
the womans suit says the driver took her to a secluded area and 
raped her her lawyers said the rape impregnated her and resulted 
in the birth of a child 
a federal judge dismissed the suit but a threejudge panel of 
the 9th us circuit court of appeals voting 21 reinstated it 
the woman has raised a genuine issue of fact tending to show 
that trooper ostrander acted with deliberate indifference to her 
interest in personal security under the 14th amendment the 
appeals court panel said 
the appeals court panel discounted the fact that a 24hour gas 
station and a 24hour convenience store both welllighted were 
located within two blocks of where ostrander left the woman 
it is for the trier of fact to determine whether a reasonable 
person should have regarded a gas station or a convenience store 
located in a highcrime neighborhood as some kind of safe haven 
where she would have been given assistance or permitted to stay 
until daybreak before walking five miles home the appeals court 
said 
the womans suit said she could not call her parents for help 
because both are disabled 
in the cleveland case the court without comment let stand a 
ruling that overturned the award against the transit system 
the cleveland woman was attacked the evening of jan 15 1985 
after getting off a train at a station in east cleveland 
her assailant later confessed to raping her as well as another 
woman at the same station the previous night 
the woman sued the greater cleveland regional transit authority 
for negligence she said the public agency failed to provide 
adequate security for passengers particularly in light of the rape 
the previous night 
a state court jury awarded her 750000 after also hearing 
evidence that numerous violent crimes were committed at the station 
from 1975 to 1985 
a state appeals court threw out the award last year 
the appeals court relied on an ohio supreme court ruling that 
police may not be sued for failing to protect the public against 
crimes unless it can be shown they owed a special duty of 
care to a crime victim 
the appeals court said it saw no difference between a regional 
transit agency and a city police department 
 
the cases are ostrander vs wood 891409 and shelton vs 
greater cleveland regional transit authority 90430 
