<TEXT>
the supreme court today refused to kill a 
civil rights lawsuit against a texas city that cracked down on 
cruising teenagers five years ago 
the court without comment left intact a ruling that forces 
desoto texas and nine members of its police department to defend 
themselves at trial against allegations of illegal arrests 
in the early 1980s desotos hampton road became a popular 
cruising spot on weekend and summer nights for teenagers from 
tarrant dallas and ellis counties on those nights hundreds of 
vehicles would drive up and down the road and hundreds of teens 
would congregate in business parking lots 
there was some vandalism but the biggest problem was litter 
evictions warnings by police distribution of leaflets and 
speeches about trespass laws had little effect 
on the night of may 3 1985 desoto police accompanied by dallas 
county sheriffs deputies and constables descended on several 
parking lots and arrested about 50 people 
six arrested teens sued the city and nine police department 
members in federal court the suit seeking monetary damages 
alleged the teens civil rights had been violated by illegal police 
arrests 
a federal judge threw out the suit ruling that the city and its 
police department were entitled to a qualified immunity from being 
sued but the 5th us circuit court of appeals reinstated the suit 
last may 
in a biting opinion the appeals court said the case should 
proceed to trial 
no doubt some of the arrestees had received prior warnings and 
deserved little sympathy for what happened to them that evening 
the appeals court said the same cannot be said for everyone 
take for example the girls on the grand prairie softball team 
the appeals court noted that four high school girls from grand 
prairie in desoto for the first time to play in a softball 
tournament had pulled into a parking lot two minutes before the 
police sweep began 
the girls who cooperated at all times with police and other 
authorities were arrested handcuffed and forced to spend the 
night in jail 
it did not stop there the 5th circuit court wrote the 
trespass charges were taken up by the criminal district attorney 
of dallas county to prove how resolute that office is against the 
