<DOCNO> AP901029-0103 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
delegates from more than 60 nations met monday to 
debate a proposed global ban on the ocean dumping of toxic 
industrial waste but the united states intends to seek further 
study before agreeing to a ban 
the proposal from denmark iceland finland norway and sweden 
calls for industrial dumping at sea to be phased by out 1995 
it will be debated tuesday by the nations at the meeting 
signatories to the london dumping convention or ldc the 
20yearold convention regulates the hauling of industrial waste to 
sea on ships 
the socalled nordic proposal calls for such dumping to be 
stopped and to do so without increasing pollution to other parts of 
the environment and without exporting waste to other countries that 
have not signed the treaty 
the proposal asks signatory nations to encourage and promote 
cleaner industrial processes recycling the treatment of waste on 
land and more research and development on alternative and 
environmentally sound means of waste disposal 
the fiveday london meeting will be closely watched by 
governments industry and environmentalists because the group is 
the only international body dealing with marine pollution 
if it can reach consensus on the current agenda it will bode 
well for future negotations on broader more complex marine issues 
such as landbased pollution of the sea 
most regulation of ocean pollution is carried out by individual 
nations or by regional groups 
as the problem of seaborne pollution has increased so have 
calls for a coordinated global response delegates will consider 
whether to expand the scope of the current treaty by beginning work 
on a new global convention on marine pollution 
about 80 percent of ocean pollution is generated on land with 
10 percent coming from industrial waste disposal and the rest 
thrown or discharged from ships 
the leader of the us delegation robert reinstein said more 
study was needed before the united states could support the ban 
reinstein is deputy assistant secretary of state for environment 
health and natural resources 
we just want to look at all the options and assess them on 
their merits he said 
britain ireland canada japan france and switzerland also 
have expressed reservations about the ban 
environmentalists accuse the united states of foot dragging and 
of taking a position in international negotiations contrary to us 
domestic law 
in 1988 congress passed the ocean dumping ban act prohibiting 
the ocean disposal of any industrial or municipal waste the 
legislation also forbade oceanbased incineration and set deadlines 
for a number of east coast cities to stop dumping municipal sewage 
the us law is one of strictest in the world on ocean dumping 
of toxic waste 
the state department idea seems to be to keep the options open 
for future dumping in case domestic law can one day be changed 
said clifton curtis an observer at the meeting from the glands 
switzerlandbased international union for the conservation of 
nature he spoke before the conference opened 
reinstein defended the decision to call for more study 
our general postion on several aspects of waste disposal is 
that we want a good scientific basis for the decisions we take 
not as a way of delaying decisions on an environmental threat but 
just as a general principle 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

