but the presiding judge added 10 years to the sentence because 
krantz had used a gun 
in its ruling last march the state supreme court rejected 
krantzs arguments that prosecutors never presented such a charge 
to a jury or proved it beyond a reasonable doubt 
in the massachusetts case two lowell police officers gary 
richardson and steven morril received a radio report that a 
convenience store clerk had seen a man with the handle of a pistol 
protruding from his pocket 
the clerk had given police a description and license number of 
the pickup truck the man had left in and the two officers stopped 
the vehicle 
richardson ordered the man paul couture out of the truck and 
then searched the drivers compartment while morril detained 
couture 
richardson found a small 38 caliber pistol for which couture 
said he did not have a license 
a state trial judge barred prosecutors from using the seized gun 
as evidence and the massachusetts supreme judicial court upheld 
that ruling 
stopping couture and searching his truck violated his fourth 
amendment protection against unreasonable police searches the 
state court ruled 
