<TEXT>
the supreme court on monday let stand a ruling 
involving black voters rights that forces norfolk va to change 
the way city council members are elected 
the court without comment rejected an appeal by city officials 
on a ruling that the atlarge system used since 1918 in city 
council elections violates black voters rights 
at the same time the justices left intact the way sagauche 
county colo elects its governing board despite claims by hispanic 
residents who say their political clout is being blunted illegally 
the court also asked the bush administration for its views of an 
appeal by a rural arkansas countys black voters who say the 
election system used in party primaries and countywide general 
elections is racially biased 
in the norfolk case a federal appeals court panel ordered the 
city to switch to a singledistrict election system that will 
remedy the vote dilution arising out of the atlarge election 
system 
the norfolk city council has seven members elected to staggered 
fouryear terms elections for three or four of the council seats 
are held every two years candidates with the most votes citywide 
win and do not need a majority of the votes cast 
a group of black voters and the local chapter of the national 
association for the advancement of colored people sued in 1983 
contending that the atlarge system illegally blunted the political 
clout of black voters 
norfolk one of virginias largest cities is 35 percent black 
in population blacks also comprise 35 percent of the citys 
registered voters 
the city council did not have a black member until 1968 and 
since then has had one black member most years 
the naacp and black voters who sued said if city council members 
were elected from seven singlemember districts black voters would 
be in the majority in three of the seven districts 
the colorado case centered on how saguache countys three 
commissioners are elected no hispanic has ever won a contested 
election in the county even though hispanics comprise 41 percent of 
the population 
the three commissioners must reside in different districts but 
elections are countywide and not confined to the district in which 
a candidate resides 
the stillpending arkansas case involves a law under which a 
candidate for a political partys nomination or for a countywide 
office must get a majority of the votes cast 
if no candidate wins an outright majority a runoff election is 
held two weeks later between the top two votegetters 
the justices were told that arkansas is one of 10 states 
employing such a system all of them in the south and all of them 
with a long history of purposeful racial vote dilution 
the other states were identified as alabama florida georgia 
louisiana mississippi north carolina south carolina texas and 
oklahoma 
the runoff system as it operates in phillips county ark was 
challenged as illegal by black voters who say their voting power is 
being diluted 
blacks comprise 47 percent of the votingage population in 
phillips county but no black candidate in modern times has 
received the democratic or republican nomination for or been 
elected to any countywide office 
the justice department in august sued to overturn georgias 
majority vote runoff system saying it has a chilling effect on 
black political participation 
some political observers say eliminating runoffs could help 
republicans in the south and southwest blacks and hispanics would 
win more democratic primaries they say only to lose general 
elections to gop candidates backed by white voters who had 
supported white democratic primary candidates 
</TEXT>
