said in his council speech we join the council in this demand 
and we urge the government of iraq to comply but i want to 
underscore one point the united states will do that which is 
necessary to meet its obligation to its own citizens 
abdul amir alanbari iraqs ambassador to the united nations 
rejected the resolution he said the security council was applying 
a double standard in dealing more harshly with iraqs invasion of 
kuwait than with israels occupation of arab territories 
pickering said the iraqi speech was the greatest pack of 
distortions lies and bizarre tales that i have ever seen it was 
like bringing the fox in to advise on how to guard the henhouse 
the resolution also demands that iraq allow foreign governments 
to send supplies to their diplomats in occupied kuwait city the 
united states and britain are the only western nations with 
embassies still operating in kuwait 
the resolution which cites violations of the fourth geneva 
convention also hints at a future war crimes inquiry there was no 
specific mention of a tribunal or reparations 
the resolution did not establish a mechanism for collecting 
compensation but said all states should assemble information about 
losses of life injury and torture loss of revenue damage and 
loss of property 
the military meeting the highestlevel in many years at the 
united nations included lt gen michael carns director of the 
joint staff of the united states and colgen bronislav a 
omelichev first deputy chief of the soviet army 
the soviet union consistently has sought revival of the security 
councils military staffcommittee and has said it only would join 
an international military action in the gulf under a un umbrella 
during the security council meeting monday ethiopias envoy 
declared iraq shall be held accountable and indeed responsible 
for the lawlessness of its occupation forces and face the attendant 
consequences 
ambassador tesfaye tadesse told the council on behalf of the 
nonaligned movement and the organization of african unity that 
iraq has refused to comply with the will of the international 
community there is not the slightest indication from baghdad of 
any change of heart he said 
the council is left with no choice he said but to send a 
message that the unity and resolve of the council to end the iraqi 
occupation of kuwait is as strong as ever 
the resolution demands that iraqi forces stop mistreating and 
oppressing kuwaiti and other nationals 
it demands that iraq ensure immediate access to food water and 
basic services for kuwaiti nationals and foreigners in kuwait and 
iraq including diplomatic missions in kuwait 
western diplomats said privately that this could be the last 
resolution exhorting iraq to obey its resolutions and indicated the 
council would adopt a more actionoriented posture 
the council has been acting under chapter 7 which provides for 
security council sanctions and even collective military action 
against member states which threaten international peace and 
security 
the council already has invoked article 41 but has not exhausted 
its nonmilitary provisions which include interruption of economic 
relations and of rail sea air postal telegraphic radio and 
other means of communication 
article 42 the next step envisoned by some members calls for 
such action by air sea or land forces as may be necessary to 
maintain or restore international peace and security including 
demonstrations blockade and other operations by air sea or land 
forces of members of the united nations 
the security council includes the five permanent members with 
veto power the united states britain china france and the 
soviet union and 10 nonpermanent members canada colombia cuba 
ethiopia finland ivory coast malaysia romania yemen zaire 
