<TEXT>
william french smith one of ronald reagans 
kitchen cabinet confidants who helped make the former president a 
millionaire and served as his first attorney general died monday 
of cancer he was 73 
smith led the reagan administrations conservative shift on a 
number of issues affecting domestic policy notably civil rights 
under his influence the administration took a more 
laissezfaire attitude toward antitrust law even though it 
presided over the breakup of the american telephone and telegraph 
co 
a navy officer during world war ii smith later became reagans 
personal attorney helping guide the investments that made the 
former actor a millionaire 
smith served as the informal chairman of the presidents kitchen 
cabinet a group of california millionaires who saw reagan socially 
and helped pick his first cabinet others in the group included 
justin dart walter annenberg verne orr william clark alfred 
bloomingdale and holmes tuttle 
smith was surrounded by his family when he died at the 
university of southern californias kenneth norris jr cancer 
hospital where he was admitted oct 2 said spokeswoman betsy 
bates 
ms bates said that at the request of the family the hospital 
withheld details on smiths cancer 
william french smith served his country with the greatest 
dedication and distinction reagan said in a statement as 
attorney general he brought talent wisdom and the highest 
integrity to the department of justice 
nancy and i are deeply saddened today he said we have 
lost a dear friend who we will always remember with the greatest 
respect and affection 
norman barker managing partner of gibson dunn amp crutcher the 
prestigious los angeles law firm smith joined after leaving the 
navy in 1946 said smiths list of accomplishments go on and on 
and on smith was the firms specialist in corporate relations 
with labor 
a member of an old new england family smith was born aug 26 
1917 in wilton nh and raised in boston he graduated from the 
university of california at berkeley in 1939 and received his law 
degree from harvard in 1942 
smith was appointed the 74th attorney general of the united 
states in 1981 and served until 1985 he was followed by edwin 
meese iii 
at his confirmation hearings the publicityshy smith responded 
to virtually every question by saying he would have to study the 
matter 
early in his tenure a magazine story quoted an administration 
official as calling him a somnambulist or sleepwalker a 
description that rankled him 
but if he started slower than his predecessors smith altered 
more department policies more sharply than any attorney general in 
a generation 
among the changes in which he played a key role were the 
appointment of the first woman sandra day oconnor to the supreme 
court legislation overturning a 100yearold ban on military aid 
to civilian law enforcement relaxation of rules against corporate 
mergers which had not been changed in 15 years and halting the 
justice departments advocacy of mandatory busing to desegregate 
schools and of hiring and promotion goals to remedy job 
discrimination 
solicitor general kenneth starr who served as a partner in 
smiths law firm and later as his chief of staff in the justice 
department called his former law partner and mentor an immensely 
gifted lawyer with marvelous sound and wise judgement and 
unfailingly kind and thoughtful 
it was one of the ironies of his tenure that it was a tenure 
characterized by such farreaching and profound change in the 
direction of the federal legal system that it was done in a 
quintessentially quiet prudent and lawyerlike fashion starr 
said 
terry h eastland a former aide to smith and later the justice 
departments chief spokesman under meese said smith was someone 
who was concerned about getting the law right about doing the 
right thing in a particular instance 
eastland now a conservative commentator and legal affairs 
writer and starr credited smith with formulating the reagan 
administrations response to the growing drug problem the regional 
task forces for the drug enforcement administration were set up 
under smiths leadership 
he was one of the early proponents of the proposition that 
drugs are causing crime starr said he felt strongly about 
that 
former appellate judge robert h bork whose supreme court 
nomination was defeated by the senate in 1988 called smith a 
very thoughtful man who played a lowkey but important role in 
picking judges for the federal bench 
since he was the one who talked me into becoming a judge i 
happened to think he is a good judge of judges said bork who 
was appointed to the us circuit court of appeals for the district 
of columbia by reagan 
smith was one of 60 patients being treated at the kenneth norris 
jr hospital which specializes in experimental treatment ms 
bates said she did not know if smith was undergoing experimental 
treatment 
the hospital is associated with the university of southern 
california and is one of 24 comprehensive cancer centers in the 
nation designated by the national institutes of health 
</TEXT>
