<TEXT>
the widow of a brewery worker who became 
an alcoholic taking advantage of free beer at work is entitled to 
workers compensation benefits an appeals court said in a ruling 
issued monday 
ruling on the case of casimer a gacioch who worked at the 
stroh brewery co the state court of appeals said alcoholism is 
like any disease and workers are entitled to compensation if the 
work environment aggravates their condition 
while gacioch was predisposed to alcoholism before the brewery 
hired him he was not an alcoholic when he got the job the court 
said 
the circumstances of the job shaped the course of gaciochs 
disease the court said aggravating and accelerating the 
underlying alcoholic predisposition to the point of uncontrolled 
addiction thus constituting a personal injury under worker 
compensation laws 
gacioch drank only three or four beers on weekends when he began 
working on the assembly line at strohs in 1947 said norton cohen 
an attorney for gaciochs widow wanda 
strohs policy following a 300yearold european tradition 
permitted workers to drink all the beer they wanted during breaks 
and that contributed to gaciochs alcoholism cohen said 
by the time he was fired in 1974 gacioch was drinking 12 
bottles of beer a day cohen said 
gacioch died in 1977 when his hospital bed caught fire while he 
was smoking at the time he was being treated for severe liver 
problems caused by his drinking his widow could receive 106 a 
week in workers compensation benefits 
an attorney for the brewery failed to return a telephone call 
seeking comment 
