<TEXT>
joseph kelly crockett snuggled next to his 
mother too young to do much of anything except eat sleep and cry 
too young to know that he is starting life a step behind most other 
babies 
despite citywide efforts to improve health care services and 
lower indianapolis skyhigh infant mortality rate josephs mother 
struggled to get caseworkers at the marion county welfare 
department to extend medicaid to her fourth child 
they dont care or they dont want to care said lisa 
carter 24 its too much of a headache for them its almost as 
if youre asking them for 20 out of their pocket 
joseph was born prematurely he was delivered at 36 weeks by 
emergency caesarian and weighed 5 pounds and it took seven weeks 
before joseph was added to the welfare rolls before he could 
receive medicaid aid to families with dependent children food 
stamps 
in the interim the pediatrician and hospital didnt press for 
payment but miss carter had to pay for his food and transportation 
to the doctor herself 
josephs father tried to help but judging from the support he 
gave lisa during her pregnancy she knows she couldnt count on 
him 
nor could she count on the welfare department the conscientious 
caseworker who handled her file for two years recently quit with 
her departure returned the threats that the familys medicaid and 
aid to families with dependent children would be cut off because of 
improper paperwork 
but then miss carter says her medicaid coverage has been taken 
away twice both times unjustly she believes 
miss carter was 5 when her mother was murdered but she overcame 
that to become an a student in school 
at 16 her first child taron smith was born but she overcame 
that to graduate from high school 
two years later she was working toward an associates degree in 
secretarial sciences when her grandmother became ill she quit 
school to care for her and never returned 
at 19 her daughter shenika was born weighing just 4 pounds 12 
ounces miss carter had become a single teenage mother with two 
young children and she couldnt find a way out 
im not stupid but i have had plenty of tragic situations in 
my life she said but i cant use that as a crutch 
in indiana a family of four must be living below 327 percent 
of the federal poverty level bringing in less than 385 a month 
to be eligible for medicaid and afdc only alabama arkansas 
louisiana new mexico north carolina texas and west virginia have 
stricter standards 
for pregnant women and children under 6 years old the picture 
is brighter because of federal mandates 
in april congress required all states to provide medicaid 
coverage to pregnant women and young children with family incomes 
below 133 percent of the federal poverty level 1972 per month 
for a family of four 
miss carter feeds clothes and shelters her family on child 
support she receives from the childrens fathers and on her 405 in 
monthly afdc payments the states maximum payment for a family of 
five thirtysix states have higher payments 
even a parttime job at minumum wage would boost her income 
