<TEXT>
king county superior court is no longer hooked on 
drug cases thanks partly to private lawyers who served as 
prosecutors without cost to the taxpayers 
about a dozen exprosecutors and 30 relatively new lawyers 
helped clear a backlog of 512 felony cases most involving 
possession of illegal drugs or intent to sell court officials 
said 
it was a signal success no question about it prosecuting 
attorney norm maleng said were going to continue to have the 
private bar involved on a pro bono basis 
precise statistics have not been compiled but maleng said the 
conviction rate appeared to be just slightly less than the 80 
percent for cases handled by staff prosecutors 
pro bono work in which private lawyers are paid by their firms 
or simply agree to handle cases without a fee has long been common 
in criminal law 
only recently however has the practice emerged as a potential 
panacea to the volume of drug cases that plague prosecutors 
nationwide said richard l wintory director of the national drug 
prosecution center for the national district attorneys association 
in alexandria va 
san diego has a wellestablished pro bono prosecutor program 
and for nearly two years the delaware state attorney generals 
office has had a lendaprosecutor agreement with a new york 
law firm across washington state a similar effort has been 
mounted in spokane the delaware program is being challenged in the 
appeal of a drunkendriving conviction in court of common pleas in 
wilmington 
wintory said publicity on seattles crash program this summer 
drew so much interest that he has begun a survey of prosecutors in 
115 jurisdictions nationwide to identify other helpful programs 
drug case filings have more than doubled in many of the nations 
4000 prosecutors offices but we havent had anywhere near this 
increase in prosecutor resources he said of seattles program 
the attraction for most participants and their employers to the 
volunteer prosecutor program is accelerated trial experience in 
addition some former prosecutors who left for higher pay in the 
private sector miss their old work 
jesse franklin two years into private practice after five years 
in malengs office returned parttime for his first experience in 
directing other lawyers he supervised about 10 cases 
i love doing the supervising i get a kick out of it partly 
because i enjoy being a prosecutor so much he said you kind 
of relive some of your old war stories 
reaction from defense lawyers has ranged from muted demurrals to 
the legal challenge in delaware 
its sort of a novelty to be doing it for the prosecution 
said bob boruchowitz director of the nonprofit seattleking 
county defender association 
the defense side is much more in need of resources than the 
prosecution boruchowitz said the pressure it put on our 
lawyers the strain on our lawyers was significant many of our 
lawyers were on backtoback trials 
presiding judge charles v johnson said he was more concerned 
about overloading the 15 regular judges during the program which 
ran from july 25 to aug 31 
parttime service on the bench was enlisted from 22 superior 
court judges from other counties three lawyers who served as pro 
tem judges and 14 court commissioners judges from appellate and 
other courts and retired jurists 
we effectively had 12 additional judges maleng said 
from our standpoint the program was a success an outstanding 
success johnson said 
boruchowitz contended the seattle program resulted in trials by 
volunteer prosecutors hungry for litigation in cases that usually 
would have been settled with plea bargains 
wintory however said temporary prosecutors could ease 
pressures to allow guilty pleas on reduced charges as an 
alternative to dismissal for lack of preparation or failure to meet 
speedy trial requirements 
kathryn mauk hired fresh out of law school by a firm that 
handles mostly insurance cases said she changed her career focus 
after spending about a quarter to a third of her time as a 
temporary prosecutor this summer 
she won a conviction in her first case a fiveday trial on a 
charge of possession of drugs with intent to deliver charges were 
dismissed in another case because of an improper arrest and three 
others ended in guilty pleas 
its exhilarating its challenging she said it moves 
quickly you have to think on your feet you have to be on its 
a different kind of high 
</TEXT>
