<TEXT>
a summary of developments in the news industry for the week of 
oct 2229 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
daily news reporters and photographers wavered 
but then decided oct 28 to remain on strike rather than take up an 
offer to cross picket lines and reclaim their jobs 
were willing to give the strike more time reporter paul 
larosa said theres no point in going back now 
the news hit by a walkout oct 25 by nine of its 10 unions had 
said striking workers were welcome to return to their old jobs at 
any time as long as permanent replacements had not been hired 
a group of about 40 reporters and photographers belonging to the 
750member newspaper guild sent a delegation to discuss the matter 
with guild president barry lipton 
some complained the guilds strike was called on the basis of a 
false report that replacements had already been hired to fill 
reporting slots 
theres a lot of anger at the guild leadership said 
striking reporter joanne wasserman 
but after the meeting the group decided to stay on strike 
no new talks were scheduled the news said it planned to replace 
the strikers permanently 
the daily news the nations secondlargest metropolitan daily 
has published a paper each day since the strike began but conceded 
it is having trouble delivering the paper 
home delivery was spotty and many newsstands were not getting 
the newspaper we have not been hitting all distribution points 
as of yet john t sloan the newspapers chief spokesman said 
oct 28 we will soon 
he also accused strikers of intimidating dealers and removing 
papers from newsstands 
strikers have burned several delivery trucks and vandalized 
others about 20 strikers have been arrested since the strike 
began most on disorderly conduct charges 
workers at the a amp s stationery store in brooklyn said 
clubwielding men had seized all 300 copies of the sunday edition 
of the news and scattered them in the gutter i cant take the 
paper or they will kill me said one of the stores owners ali 
najeli 
the new york times quoted an unidentified management source as 
saying many drivers had become lost 
the news said in a statement that it published and distributed 
more than 12 million sunday papers in the city and surrounding 
suburbs exceeding the previous days press run by 500000 the 
news normally prints 146 million sunday papers 
the 71yearold daily has been in a financial tailspin for a 
decade the news has lost about 115 million and seen daily 
circulation slip by about 700000 since 1980 it recently lost its 
standing as the nations largest metropolitan daily to the los 
angeles times 
the strike began when 60 drivers at the news were replaced in a 
dispute over whether a driver would be allowed to monitor a 
conveyor belt while sitting down the other unions followed suit 
the unions claimed management provoked the crisis which 
followed 10 months of often stormy talks on contracts to replace 
those that expired in march 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
the tribune co reported a 39 percent decline in 
aftertax profit for the third quarter due to operating losses at 
its canadian paper mills and the new york daily news 
the company said oct 22 that net income fell to 382 million 
or 52 cents a share from 627 million or 81 cents a share 
during the same period last year revenue slipped 05 percent to 
588 million from 5907 million 
newspaper operating profit fell 15 percent for the quarter to 
484 million from 567 million last year due to losses at the 
daily news the company attributed the losses at the daily news to 
weak economic conditions in the new york market and what it calls a 
burdensome cost structure which was at the heart of long labor 
negotiations that boiled over into the strike oct 25 
profits for the remainder of the newspaper group which includes 
the chicago tribune and the orlando fla sentinel were down 
slightly the company said 
for the third quarter the companys quebec and ontario paper 
co reported a loss of 83 million compared to a profit of 152 
million last year strikes by the canadian paperworkers union shut 
down the quebec newsprint mill for 31 days and the ontario mill for 
47 days 
for the first three quarters net income was down 27 percent at 
1279 million or 173 a share from 1748 million or 227 a 
share last year revenue rose 2 percent to 183 billion from 
179 billion 
