the taiwan government has reached an 
outofcourt settlement with the widow of a chineseamerican 
journalist murdered by gangsters hired by a nationalist admiral 
the foreign ministry reported 
ministry spokesman huang hsinpi said oct 26 that the 
settlement was not an acknowledgement of responsibility by the 
nationalist government for the murder of henry liu liu was a 
columnist for a chinese newspaper in san francisco whose writings 
were critical of the taiwan government 
huang declined to provide details of the settlement but taiwan 
newspapers said lius widow helen received 15 million 
liu 52 was shot to death in 1984 in the garage of his home 
south of san francisco by gunmen who were later identified as 
members of taiwans united bamboo gang 
he had earlier written a critical biography of thentaiwan 
president chiang chingkuo helen liu who claimed the murder was 
politically motivated filed a 200 million suit against taiwan 
authorities in us courts claiming they were behind the killing 
last year the 9th us circuit court of appeal ruled that the 
taiwan government was legally responsible for the acts of former 
military intelligence chief vice admiral wong hsiling who was 
sentenced to life imprisonment by a taiwan military court in 1985 
for ordering three gangsters to murder liu 
the taiwan government appealed the verdict to the us supreme 
court officials said the appeal had been dropped because of the 
outofcourt settlement 
</TEXT>
