<TEXT>
 
editors note the kibitzers this night include a playwright 
from spain a drug dealer a queens housewife a master chess 
player from harlem a biker and assorted yuppies they are in a 
hotel next door to the old theater where garry kasparov and anatoly 
karpov sit hunched over their chessboard they watch the action on 
closedcircuit tv and debate the players every move their 
politics their diet their very nose scratchings 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
chess notes from a witness who doesnt know a 
nimzoindian opening from a hole in his sock 
in worldtitle chess the kibitzer not a piece of carved wood 
is king 
garry kasparov is defending his world title against anatoly 
karpov in the absolute silence of the old hudson theater lately 
sunk from the grandeur of the opening of eugene oneills strange 
interlude to times square porno flicks but now resurrected for 
kings pawn openings 
the only infrequent sound is shshshsh an observer 
corks off into snores he is immediately poked awake from three 
directions an elderly spectator noisily unbrownbags a sandwich 
an usher ushers him out 
but next door in the hotel macklowe which owns the hudson and 
is chess headquarters hundreds thousands debate the players 
every move their politics their diet their very nose 
scratchings 
the macklowe is a tower of babble from the lowest patzer 
german to make a mess of things to the highest grandmasters 
many tongues all at once 
some 150 chess fans are crowded in a windowless lecture room of 
the macklowe to hear roman dzindzichashvili luckily he answers to 
either roman or dzindzi pronounced gingi analyze the 
contest from closedcircuit tv 
kasparov will never make that move never says gingi 
wielding his pointer at the tv screen he will never do it 
without first visiting bar 
gingi a rumpled russian emigre with the hairdo of an astrakhan 
sheep once no 6 in the chess world and twice us champion 
speaks english with no thes 
kasparov after deliberating longer than the average ice age 
makes that move the kibitzers genially boo gingi 
i boo you back 
gingi survives the storm bets a lollipop on karpovs next move 
with mark rubinstein of brooklyn gingis gambit declined mark is 
up beyond his bedtime he is 11 
karpov after another ice age moves a bishop 
anybody can kibitz which may be the allure of this sport if it 
is a sport walter mittys can fantasize they aced ivan lendl at 
wimbledon or faked a free safety out of his jock to catch one from 
joe montana in the end zone but these are only the fields of 
dreams 
in gingis lecture room many fans ponder on their pocket 
chessboards the same imponderable kasparovkarpov ponder they are 
in the game 
tonights kibitzers games start at 530 pm and run five 
hours in gingis room include a playwright from spain a drug 
dealer who shall be nameless a queens housewife a motorcycle type 
in leather jacket with a pile of bud cans growing at his feet 
jerald times 27 a master from harlem assorted briefcased 
yuppies one other woman rafael knopler who told them back home 
in israel he had to go to new york on business and ben heller 
also from queens torn between the game and the latest train he can 
catch before manhattans streets turn mean he keeps glancing 
nervously at his watch 
do these guys ever cheat asks the only other woman present 
im hired by international chess federation not national 
enquirer gingi answers 
kasparovs knight to square c4 
kasparov in the finest tradition of chess hates karpov thinks 
hes evil a creature of darkness karpov 37 was a favorite 
of the pregorby kremlin kasparov 27 half jewish and all 
armenian was not in fact hes red hot for democracy he pasted a 
prerevolution russian flag on his side of the table karpov 
protested kasparov counterprotested karpovs hammer and sickle 
flag both flags went a draw 
the two have played 120 games before this 24game world 
championship garry has won 17 anatoly 16 the other 87 were 
draws there is a partition under the table separating their feet 
kicking is out 
karpov bishop to a6 
other than bushgorbachev and perhaps some hostile wall street 
takeovers this match is the only summit encounter conducted in 
business suits this is misleading chess takes no prisoners 
ben franklin said of chess etiquette you should not sing nor 
whistle nor look at your watch nor make a tapping with your feet 
wilhelm steinitz an austrian world champ 188694 once spat at his 
opponent 
a perfect porcupine said a contemporary of steinitz known 
as a poor loser and worse winner wherever you touched him was a 
sharp point 
aran nimzovich deviser of the nimzoindian once swept the 
pieces off the board crying why must i lose to this idiot 
he also did knee bends and stood on his head while his rival was 
trying to concentrate 
emanuel lasker german world champ 18941921 would exhale a 
virtual gas attack of cigar smoke across the table one 
tournament organizer protested that lasker smoked the finest 
havanas away from the chessboard but switched to stinking nickel 
rockets in competition the russian world title holder michael 
botvinnik 194657 used to train by having a sparring partner blow 
smoke in his face during practice 
when siegbert tarrasch challenged lasker in 1908 he began and 
concluded his dialogue with the champion thusly i have only 
three words to say to you in this match check and mate 
in keeping with the lowest level of sportsmanship at the highest 
level of chess tarrasch as have many others blamed his defeat on 
poor health the match held in dusseldorf was too close to 
debilitating sea air he complained dusseldorf was and presumably 
still is 170 miles from the nearest coast 
kasparov puts a rook in play 
are both sides still equal a kibitzer asks gingi 
one side is equal other has advantage the grandmaster 
hedges without elaboration 
