<TEXT>
oneupmanship is an essential part of the kibitzers arsenal a 
heavy european accent delivering profundities that mean nothing 
helps if you say kusparoff correct and he says kasparoff 
hes obviously a patzer he says aleckein alexander alekhine was 
a universally despised world champion drunk lecher and 
antisemite between the world wars and an immortal who fidgeted 
like a dog on an ant hill pronouncing it something like the name 
of the tigers hall of fame rightfielder al kaline if you say it 
right alyekchin you are a grandmaster and he is a nikulturny 
kasparov makes a move to no discernible pattern 
there may be something sneaky in kasparovs mind says the 
lady from queens 
this absolutely sneakless move says gingi sipping a soda 
kasparov is known for a relentless attacking style karpov for 
defense in depth like the russians defending moscow from napoleon 
one columnist has said garry has been all but berserk in 
earlier matches even though to the untrained eye he has been as 
immobile as rodins thinker except for minor league twitchings 
and ear pulls 
karpovs men are in a gligoric variation kasparovs with a 
knight split wide 
kasparov who has the highest number of rating points in the 
history of chess has the type of mind that could do a sunday 
crossword puzzle in his head 
he holds that head in his hands fingers splayed around his 
ears hand then adjusts a sleeve of his black suit recrosses legs 
pinches nose cups chin in hand makes bipod of forearms resting 
nose on clasped fingers glares down athis men only inches away 
like drill inspector at parris island reviewing recruits after 23 
minutes 
kasparov knight to f4 
queens housewife why do they take so long 
gingi they dont want to play nearly best move they want to 
play best move they take time because they have time 
in a 41move game it would take 1000 billion generations to 
play every possible combination at a fraction of a second per move 
were getting there 
chess is a game of memory technique imagination and intuition 
the top grandmasters know an infinitude of moves from the maroozy 
bind variation of the sicilian defense to queens gambit declined 
the french poisoned pawn the velimirovic attack 
they constantly study past games of their opponent and 
masterpiece games of the ages anderssens immortal in london 
1851 the pearl of zandvoort max euwe versus alekhine in 1935 
frank marshalls 23rd move at breslau in 1912 
all the while said saviely tartakower an austrian grandmaster 
earlier in this century the blunders are there all waiting to 
be made 
the queens of both kasparov and karpov are dead 
chess kept me out of trouble says jerald times the young 
harlem master i was a good kid but it gave me pride in 
intellect a ballerina has to stretch her body same thing in 
chess it stretches your mind 
times has survived a broken ghetto home got to college now 
teaches poetry to the homeless dropouts kids in the violent 
classrooms of the city 
chess he says takes more exertion than fullcourt basketball 
in summers he plays chess in harlem parks until early morning his 
rapid articulation pauses when he considers what other harlem kids 
have done in parks in new york 
chess 
the freewheeling end game has begun 
why does kasparov always use the kings indian defense asks 
ben heller 
because he knows it it works for him says gingi you 
have job you go to it every day why dont you change 
heller leaves for his train 
gingi says it looks like a draw no draw says the queens 
housewife i want my 25 bucks worth 
in 1924 the soviet unions third allunion congress decided 
chess was a weapon in the struggle for a higher cultural level 
and made the game a vehicle to show the world the superiority of 
communism the soviet union has held the world title since 1946 
with but one exception that was the american bobby fischer who 
brought rudeness neurosis brilliance and prize money to an 
alltime high in winning the title from boris spassky in iceland in 
1972 
fischer thereupon turned his back on multimilliondollar gates 
to lead a demonic reclusive life among the derelict hotels in the 
los angeles area half jewish he has reportedly become an ardent 
admirer of adolf hitler but kasparovkarpov can thank fischers 
histrionics for making the 3 million prize money for their match 
possible 
eccentricity if not madness is a not uncommon end game for chess 
players paul morphy of new orleans blazed briefly in the 1850s and 
is considered one of the best ever later he took to wandering the 
streets claiming his friends turned enemies and were trying to 
steal his clothes a polish grandmaster named frydman stripped 
during a tournament and ran through the hotel crying fire 
steinitz went mad 
perhaps the most normal of the very greatest was jose raul 
capablanca a cuban who played basketball while at columbia college 
and once was late for a match having just left the bed of the 
mistress of a grand duke 
examples of mental turmoil coupled with the intricacies of the 
game give a popular impression that chess is a game for weirdo 
geniuses 
but a team of russian psychologists made a study and found no 
relationship between chess and general intelligence capablanca 
who was put on the payroll of the cuban foreign office and posted 
as a goodwill ambassador to wherever he had a tournament said of 
the game which he found as effortless as his love life 
to play chess requires no intelligence at all 
gingi is right karpov offers a draw leaving the match 32 
for kasparov with seven more games to go at the hudson and 12 more 
if needed in lyons france 
mark rubinstein goes to the souvenir room to browse through 
chess books and tshirts it was boring he kibitzes 
could he take the champ 
in three years says mark an 11yearold monday quarterback 
plotting moves on his board of dreams 
