<TEXT>
fiddler mark oconnor has played on 
grammywinning albums and become one of the most soughtafter 
instrumentalists in the music business but the master musician 
doesnt think hes mastered anything 
what im doing is the best i can at this time the day when i 
get something mastered would be the day id have to quit doing 
it he says 
the 29yearold oconnor describes an intimate almost poetic 
relationship with his fiddle it is a pairing that has made him 
virtually peerless for his versatility 
you establish this relationship as a duo you work together 
handinhand and try to make it come alive he says if you 
respect your instrument it can give a lot back to you music is an 
inner thing you try to achieve the relationship becomes intense 
oconnor can be heard playing as a sessions musician on 
countless albums recorded in nashville he has released nine albums 
of his own first for rounder records and more recently for mca 
records 
the country music foundation has just issued the lp mark 
oconnor the championship years the cuts include his winning 
performances between 1975 and 1984 at the national old time 
fiddlers contest in weiser idaho 
hes even given a command performance of sorts about 10 years 
ago he was a guest at former president ronald reagans ranch in 
california where he performed as one of the countrys top young 
musicians he played sweet georgia brown during an appearance 
that became part of a special on public television 
i was about as nervous as ive ever been the softspoken 
oconnor recalled in an interview i was almost white as a ghost 
but as an american musician it was one of the most rewarding 
things you could do 
oconnor a native of seattle taught himself to play fiddle at 
age 11 by watching others naturally gifted he was also proficient 
on the guitar banjo mandolin and dobro but the fiddle became his 
instrument of choice 
it seems like im a little bit more naturally expressive on 
it he said 
he has made concert tours with the rockfusion band dixie dregs 
and with jazz master stephane grappelli he played on michael 
breckers grammywinning jazz lp in 1989 dont try this at 
home and collaborated with james taylor on taylors album 
never die young he has won frets magazines best 
instrumentalist award six times 
oconnor has played on just about every style of record 
possible 
the variety of it is amazing he said the bulk of it is 
country and theres a lot of alternative things jazz folky pop 
contemporary christian 
music is so much a part of my being that i just walk around 
with melodies in my head all day long 
oconnor who does not sing says he loves all musical styles if 
they are played well i try to play these different styles and i 
learn a lot from every style it almost helps me play the opposing 
style better i dont get so wrapped up in the style or the idiom 
that i reject others i adapt 
even though he plays almost every day he said hes still 
learning and searching for perfection 
i feel like my mind is divided onehalf of it teaches the 
other half so onehalf of it is constantly looking for new ideas 
and new things to pick up then i train and teach myself those 
things 
the most rewarding part is improvisation playing from the 
inspiration of the moment and not knowing what youre going to do 
its a little bit mysterious and magical what it really is is 
onthespot composition youre letting it all out on the line 
oconnor doesnt think hell ever get tired of playing 
sometimes i do get tired of playing in the situations im playing 
in this happens more than tiring of the music itself i dont want 
to do one type of thing too many times im always looking for the 
ne approach 
