from trainhopping hobo to television 
celebrity its been a remarkable journey for art linkletter who 
says he never intended to get into show business in the first 
place 
i was studying to be an english professor said linkletter 
78 but as they say life is what happens to you while youre 
making other plans 
adults remember linkletter as the practical joker on nbcs 
people are funny 
his house party also known as the linkletter show ran 
24 years on radio and tv until 1969 linkletter often made kids 
the centerpiece of his routines keeping a straight face while they 
made embarrassing revelations about their parents 
family is the key we had a traditional family he said 
my wife was a private person taking care of the children family 
and house i was the breadwinner i had the fortress of my home so 
i could go out and battle the demons 
and who were these demons linkletter says everyone from 
unscrupulous competitors to thieves drugpushers and other threats 
to family health and happiness 
hoping to shield his loved ones linkletter said he developed a 
career that would enable his wife to stay at home but he found 
there are no guarantees in life 
linkletters 20yearold daughter diane jumped to her death 
from her sixthfloor hollywood apartment in 1969 while under the 
influence of lsd three months earlier the husband of his oldest 
daughter shot and killed himself in 1980 his 35yearold son 
robert was killed in a car accident 
life is not fair not easy he said outside peer 
pressure can wreak havoc with the nicest families so thats the 
part thats a gamble 
but im an optimist even though ive had tragedies in my 
life and ive seen a lot of difficult things i still am an 
optimist 
linkletters own childhood had its share of struggles 
born arthur gordon kelley linkletters preacherfather 
drenched me in religion and forced him to take odd jobs during 
the depression he said so at 16 linkletter left and became a 
hobo hopping trains across the west working where he could 
several years later linkletter returned home and entered san 
diego state college where he got his first taste of broadcasting 
he went on to national radio and finally television 
today he is recognized as the dapper silverhaired man who sells 
therapeutic contour chairs one of which he owns and occasionally 
uses 
the little kids dont know me generally linkletter said 
mothers come up to me in airports with children and say jimmy 
this is art linkletter and the poor kid looks up and says whos 
he 
of course there was a time when every kid in america knew 
me 
linkletter doesnt seem to mind that his star has faded a bit 
he owns a home in plush belair the view from his wilshire 
district office takes in the skyscrapers of downtown los angeles 
he spoke with a visitor at a big desk topped with family photos and 
a statue of an american bald eagle 
he gives 75 to 80 lectures around the country each year his 
name appears on 23 books including the bestsellers kids say the 
darndest things and old age is not for sissies his next book 
is tentatively titled how to make your child into a human 
being 
following his daughters death linkletter began a nationwide 
campaign against drug abuse he continues to speak out against 
drugs and said his faith in christianity has grown 
lois his wife of 54 years continues to live the traditional 
lifestyle spending time with her children and grandchildren she 
said the key to their long marriage and prosperity was the absence 
of competition 
what hes good at im not she said as she wallpapered her 
home with her daughter sharon his rise to the top was gradual 
for us it was a part of our lives 
sharon 44 said growing up as a linkletter was at times 
perplexing she recalled feeling awkward at a public school because 
she was a famous child she later transferred to a private school 
i think as an adult unfortunately a lot of the years growing 
up were taken for granted she said it didnt seem odd to me 
to be on tv christmas shows but as an adult i saw what an 
incredible life we had 
she now looks at her father as a man who made a whole rainbow 
out of his life he turned lemons into lemonade and rain into 
rainbows 
