louisiana has been giving sales tax back to 
foreign shoppers for a year now but while state officials are 
thrilled to see more tourists some of the visitors are frustrated 
with red tape 
the experimental taxfree shopping program has returned 1 
million in taxes to foreign tourists who spent 13 million at the 
1000 participating stores officials said the state figures the 
vistors money has brought in 2 to 4 million in tax revenue from 
increased economic activity since the program started last nov 1 
hotel restaurant and transportation taxes are not refunded 
officials had expected each foreign shopper to spend about 300 
on taxexempt purchases however its turned out to be almost 
triple that and six times what the average us tourist spends 
said jerry merlino head of the program 
for every 1 percent we increase international visitation to 
louisiana the state would gain 35 million in taxes on money 
spent on goods and services not eligible for tax refunds 
said karen kelly marketing and sales director of the program 
the weakened dollar which gives foreign tourists more spending 
power in this country has helped bring shoppers officials 
acknowledge but the sales tax rebate which in new orleans amounts 
to 9 percent has given louisiana an edge they say 
while the tourists are spending money some are leaving angry 
i need my refund now one man argued during 20 minutes of 
haggling with the refund clerk at the airport redemption center 
it wasnt explained to me before i began shopping that i 
wouldnt be able to get my money immediately said the man who 
would not give his name to a reporter i wanted the cash for when 
i traveled instead i have to wait for them to mail it to me 
officials said it could take 4 to 6 weeks for mailed refunds to 
reach their destinations 
jessica nguyen an employee at the refund center said such 
complaints are common 
