<TEXT>
kansas gas and electric co has agreed to a 
1 billion merger with kansas power and light co in a move that 
could frustrate a hostile takeover effort by another regional 
utility company 
by becoming a whollyowned subsidiary of kansas power and light 
kgampe would escape being acquired by kansas city power and light 
co which had been offering 27 a share in an 875 million tender 
offer 
the merger agreement was unanimously approved by directors of 
both companies according to a joint statement released sunday by 
the utilities 
after carefully reviewing all options management has 
concluded that this merger serves the best interest of the 
companys shareholders its customers and employees said wilson 
cadman chief executive officer of kgampe 
in reaching its decision the board determined that the 
friendly combination with the kansas power and light company was 
not only attractive to our owners but the two companys people and 
assets fit together well permitting us to better serve our 
customers cadman said 
in the consolidation each share of kgampe common stock will be 
converted into a total of 32 in cash or kansas power and light 
stock the utilities said 
if kgampe stockholders wish all cash we can accommodate that up 
to 432 million cadman said if they want all stock we can 
accommodate that or a combination of each 
john e hayes jr chairman of kansas power and light said the 
utility started to look at the consequences of company ownership 
as soon as kcpl announced the hostile bid in july 
on sept 11 kgampe announced that it was negotiating with a third 
party as a means of rebuffing the takeover attempt it had been 
widely believed that kgampe was looking for a white knight as 
kcpl persisted 
in response to the merger announcement kcpl spokesman turner 
white said this is the thing thats been anticipated for a long 
time we need to evaluate exactly what the transaction is with 
respect to ours 
excess generating capacity of kgampe had been thought to be the 
main reason for kcpls interest in the takeover kcpl has a rapidly 
growing customer base and kgampe has enough excess capacity that 
could serve as many as 100000 additional residential customers 
hayes said the merged utilities would make available to kcpl 
enough generating capacity to fulfill their customer needs into 
the late 1990s at market rates 
hayes also said customers of kgampe would benefit from a 15 
million rate reduction to be sought once the merger is final 
we believe that the combined companies will provide even more 
efficient and higher quality service not only to our current 
customers but also to new business attracted to the area by the 
availability of abundant energy at reasonable costs hayes said 
kgampe has characterized kcpls tender offer as illegal and 
inadequate 
kcpl has extended its tender offer three times reporting 
earlier this month that about 44 percent of the kgampe shares had 
been tendered 
if the deal with kanas power and light is completed kgampe would 
continue to maintain its headquarters in wichita hayes said no 
layoffs for either company were expected 
the merger was subject to approval from state and federal 
regulatory authorities 
kansas power and light is based in topeka and does business as 
kpl gas service co it has about 1 million customers in kansas 
western missouri and northeastern oklahoma and had revenues of 11 
billion in 1989 
kgampe of wichita has about 250000 customers in southcentral and 
southeast kansas it had revenues of 5334 million last year 
