<TEXT>
opponents of a philadelphia hotel room tax 
lost a supreme court appeal today 
the court without comment rejected arguments the tax 
unlawfully interferes with interstate commerce and unfairly 
discriminates against those who live outside the city 
among those challenging the tax were members of a libertarian 
group called liberty forum a wall street journal editor and a 
business consultant 
they said the tax violates their rights by forcing them to 
contribute to the construction of a proposed 523 million 
philadelphia convention center 
the philadelphia city council authorized by a state law raised 
the tax in 1986 on hotel room rentals from 3 percent to 5 percent 
the rate is to go to 6 percent after substantial completion of the 
convention center 
the higher taxes are to help finance the centers construction 
although most of the money for the project is to come from other 
sources 
challenging the tax were liberty forum members john famularo and 
linda morrison of philadelphia wall street journal editor john 
fund who lives in jersey city nj richard broglino a business 
consultant from lexington mass and stuart kessler a new york 
city architect 
they said the tax is unconstitutional because it applies only to 
those who stay at a hotel 30 days or less the great majority of 
hotel patrons subject to the tax are outofstate residents they 
said 
a pennsylvania state court upheld the tax last year the state 
court said the higher taxes paid by those challenging the levy are 
minimal when compared to the prospective good to be achieved by 
both city residents and visitors alike 
the case is morrison vs pennsylvania convention center 
authority 90equals377 
