chrysler corp reported a 214 
million thirdquarter loss monday a performance that would have 
been worse without record earnings at the companys financial 
subsidiary 
the earnings report which showed chrysler did better by loaning 
money than by building and selling cars underscored its 
difficulties as the no 3 detroit automaker negotiates with the 
united auto workers to reach a new contract 
chrysler is the last and weakest of the big three to negotiate 
with the uaw and has said it cant be as generous as rivals general 
motors corp and ford motor co 
chrysler reported a thirdquarter loss of 95 cents a share 
compared to 331 million or 142 a share in the 1989 quarter 
that period included a onetime 309 million credit from the sale 
of some stock in mitsubishi motors corp chrysler now holds an 11 
percent share of the japanese automaker 
the company said the loss stemmed partly from the cost of cash 
rebates and other incentivies aimed at selling cars as well as the 
costs of a onemonth shutdown for retooling of chryslers two 
minivan plants which make some of the companys bestselling 
vehicles 
by contrast chrysler financial corp which handles consumer 
car loans earned 83 million in the quarter ended sept 30 its 
best performance ever 
the thirdquarter loss came on revenues of 65 billion down 
145 percent from 76 billion recorded in july through september 
last year 
for the first nine months of 1990 chrysler earned 37 million 
or 17 cents a share compared with 983 million or 421 a share 
last year revenue fell 154 percent to 23 billion from 272 
billion 
chrysler lost a little less in the third quarter than i 
expected said auto analyst david healy of the investment bank 
barclays de zoete wedd noting that chrysler financial did a good 
deal better than i expected 
healy also noted that chrysler does not plan to close its st 
louis i assembly plant as soon as expected last year chrysler 
targeted a september 1990 shutdown but since pushed the closing 
back to may 1991 the end of production for the chrysler lebaron 
coupe and convertible and the dodge daytona 
healy said chrysler treasurer jerry york told wall street 
analysts monday that the companys costcutting pace has 
accelerated now that 1991 models are in production much of the 
saving is tied to more efficient manufacturing operations for the 
1991 models which officially debuted oct 1 
york also said incentive costs for the automaker should begin to 
ease 
it was about 1200 per vehicle for the second quarter and 
1250 for the third quarter healy said it will be maybe a 
little less than that in the fourth quarter 
chairman lee iacocca blamed a variety of events for the 
thirdquarter loss 
we anticipated 1990 would be a tough year for chrysler and for 
the industry so we launched a major costcutting program over a 
year ago he said in a statement we didnt anticipate the gulf 
crisis the federal budget fiasco or the continued escalation in 
the incentive wars so weve increased our costreduction goals to 
25 billion over two years 
iacocca has set the costcutting target for june 1991 
chrysler stock rose on the earnings report but fell back to 
close at 11 down 12 cents on the new york stock exchange 
ford was expected to announce thirdquarter earnings tuesday 
they were projected to be slightly more than half of the 4771 
million the company earned during the period last year 
general motors corp reports major subsidiaries earnings 
tuesday and corporate earnings wednesday the no 1 automaker is 
expected to show a 50 percent drop in thirdquarter earnings from 
the 1989 level of 5169 million 
