<DOCNO> AP901029-0262 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
minnesota insurance companies would face 
some of the strictest financial requirements in the country under 
industrysupported recommendations announced monday by the state 
commerce commissioner 
there isnt a crisis out there now but there are troubled 
companies commissioner thomas borman said in releasing a report 
from the minnesota insurance solvency task force 
the regulations are intended to boost consumer confidence in 
minnesota insurance companies and prevent insolvencies which cost 
the industry millions of dollars in payments to state guaranty 
funds 
the chief change would limit junk bond holdings to 15 percent of 
a companys assets the countrys most stringent restriction on 
low or unrated debt securities borman said new yorks 20 percent 
limit is currently the most restrictive he said 
another proposal would require insurers to mark down the value 
of distressed real estate and real estate loans to market 
values those reports would be filed with the commissioners 
office forming the basis for possible targeted examinations 
borman said he knows of no other state requiring such reports 
a third recommendation is for companies to follow a new formula 
in reporting their capital structures requiring them to account 
for risks related to underwritings and investments generally the 
formula would require additions to capital as a company invests 
in riskier assets borman said utah has a riskbased capital 
formula and new york is studying one 
to enforce the proposed changes borman said he would like at 
least 30 more insurance regulators on his staff more than tripling 
its size at an annual cost of roughly 15 million minnesota 
insurance executives on the task force said the industry would be 
willing to pay for the added expense in the form of increased fees 
but borman will first seek an appropriation from the legislature 
he said 
the changes could be enforced against the 104 insurance 
companies based in minnesota and outofstate companies applying to 
do business here borman said outofstate companies already doing 
business in the state wouldnt be held to the new regulations but 
they may be targeted for review if they are not meeting revised 
standards borman said 
i am certain that poorly managed companies will feel pain 
based on the recommendations of the task force borman said 
he said the changes are proposed as a way to target 
highflying insurance companies who invested heavily in the 
1980s in junk bonds and commercial real estate such early 
government intervention could avert the kind of trouble suffered in 
the savings and loan industry borman said 
were dealing with this in a forwardlooking way borman 
said what you had in the savings and loan industry was after the 
fact they really reacted under a crisis mentality 
more than 30 percent of junk bonds issued in the 1980s were 
purchased by us life insurance companies many of whom also are 
longterm lenders in commercial real estate borman said 
the proposed changes should not lead to higher premiums said 
task force member robert p gandrud president and chief executive 
officer of lutheran brotherhood a minneapolisbased life and 
health insurance company 
we either pay now in improved regulation or we can pay later 
we see it as an investment in insolvency prevention gandrud 
said 
borman said the state has the authority to suspend insurance 
licenses and halt sales of a company until problems are cleared up 
he said he did not know how many companies in the state would 
have to sell junk bonds or make other changes in capital structure 
to conform with proposed changes 
susan mead a spokeswoman for minneapolisbased northwestern 
national life said the law should put minnesotabased insurers at 
a competitive advantage 
the consumers can feel that if they have policies from a 
minnesota company they are pretty safe she said 
borman said he may immediately adopt some of the regulatory 
guidelines proposed by the task force but he said there would be a 
public hearing on the limits regarding junk bonds because it would 
require legislative action 
the task force was made up of four commerce department officials 
and top executives from 10 minnesotabased insurance companies 
</TEXT>
